\par \lang1033\ltrch\f6\fs40\b\i0\ul0\cf6\cb14\ 1\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ And the number...shall be\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  What is the connection of retribution and consolation juxtaposed in one 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ speech? Our Rabbis explained in Pesachim (87b): Hosea felt that he had sinned by saying, ìExchange 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ them for another nation.î He stood and begged mercy for them (See above 1:2). And in Sifrei Devei 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Rav, in the section commencing: ìAnd Israel abode in Shittimî (Num. 25) we learned: Rabbi says: 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Some sections are close to each other yet as far apart as east is far from west. ìFor you are not My 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ people... And the number of the children of Israel shall be as the sand of the sea.î What is the 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ connection of one to the other? This can be compared to a king who became angry with his wife. He 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ summoned a scribe to come and write a bill of divorcement. Before the scribe arrived, the king 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ became reconciled with his wife. Said the king, ìIs it possible that this scribe should leave here 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ divided?î I.e. his heart should be divided and bewildered, saying, ìWhy did the king send for me?î He 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ said to him, ìCome and write that I am doubling her kethubah.î And according to its simple meaning, 
